This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring December 3, 2013, as the International Day of Persons with Disabilities. The proclamation highlights the progress made in promoting inclusion, access, and equal opportunity for individuals with disabilities, both in the United States and internationally. Obama urges the Senate to ratify the Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities, which is based on the principles of the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA). The proclamation also mentions efforts by the Obama Administration to improve hiring opportunities for veterans and people with disabilities, as well as the positive impact of the Affordable Care Act on healthcare coverage for individuals with disabilities. The proclamation concludes by calling on all Americans to observe the day with appropriate ceremonies, activities, and programs.